    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Next Step to a Mineola Police Force: A Vote'' (Oct. 16):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Next Step to a Mineola Police Force: A Vote'' (Oct. 16):</p>
        <p>Studies indicate that policing efficiency is not determined by size and that, in fact, small police departments are just as effective as larger ones. Two obvious benefits of staying small and local are a higher percentage of personnel involved in hands-on police services than in larger bureaucracies and a more in-depth knowledge of community conditions.</p>
        <p>Also, suburban communities like Mineola normally do not have ongoing serious crime issues, and, if needed, assistance from other organizations is readily available.</p>
        <p>The concerns that the citizens of Mineola want adequately addressed are typically minor in nature -- disorderly teenagers, traffic problems and so on. These issues would be better served by creating their own police force.</p>
        <p>James J. Green  Sparkill, N.Y.</p>
        <p>The writer is an assistant professor of criminal justice, St. Thomas Aquinas College.</p>
      </block>
